Phiaris micana is a moth of the family Tortricidae. It is found in Europe and across the Palearctic.
The wingspan is 13â€“18 mm. The ground color of the forewings is brown with varying touches of ochre-coloured scales. In the basal part there is a relatively regular white cross-band that may have some ochre colour along the edge. In the outer part of the wing there is an irregular, white and ochre-coloured band that is often interrupted in the middle. Moreover, in the outer part they are several silvery crosslines. The hindwings are grey-brown.
The moth flies from May to July. [1].
The larvae feed on various mosses and herbaceous plants.